    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName><hi rend="smallCaps">Down, Bromley, Kent, S.C.</hi></placeName>
                        <date>10<hi rend="italic">th January</hi> 1869.</date>
                        <salute><hi rend="smallCaps">My dear Sir,—</hi></salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I write one line to say that I am ashamed of myself for having kept your book so long, partly for my son’s sake, and partly for my own sake, as I have not yet come to the place where I want to quote it. If I hear from you, I will send it at once; if I do <hi rend="italic">not</hi> hear, I will keep it for about ten days more, and will then send it registered, so you shall get it safe.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                        <p>With sincere thanks, yours very faithfully, <hi rend="smallCaps">Charles Darwin</hi>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
            </div>
           
            
           
            
           
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD evidently returned the book, a collection of Croll’s papers, in February 1869; see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 16, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6489.xml">letter from James Croll, 2 December 1868</ref> and n. 2, and <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 17, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6585.xml">letter to James Croll, 31 January [1869]</ref>. The son was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml">George Howard Darwin</ref> (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 16, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6496.xml">letter to G. H. Darwin, [9 December 1868]</ref>). CD cited Croll’s work on glaciation in <hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 5th ed., pp. 451–2.</note>
               </div>
        
